@Node "Usage" "UMSMailStat.guide/Usage"
@Toc "Main"

Using UMSMailStat
*****************

   UMSMailStat can only be started from CLI and has the following
arguments:

   @{b}*@{ub} Strings

        - @{"NAME/A" Link "NAME"}

        - @{"PASSWORD/A" Link "PASSWORD"}

        - @{"SERVER/K" Link "SERVER"}

        - @{"GROUP/A" Link "GROUP"}

        - @{"QCHRS=QUOTECHARS" Link "QUOTECHARS"}

     NAME, PASSWORD and GROUP always have to specified.

   @{b}*@{ub} To specify the period to scan:

        - @{"DATE and DAYS/N" Link "DATE & DAYS"}

   @{b}*@{ub} Numeric values:

        - @{"MU=MAXUSERS/S" Link "MAXUSERS"}

        - @{"MS=MAXSUBJECTS/S" Link "MAXSUBJECTS"}

   @{b}*@{ub} Switches:

        - @{"QUITE/S" Link "QUIET"}

        - @{"RB=REALBYTES/S" Link "REALBYTES"}

        - @{"CD=CDATE/S" Link "CDATE"}

        - @{"QCHK=QUOTECHECK/S" Link "QUOTECHECK"}

        - @{"NS=NOSUBJECTS/S and NU=NOUSERS/S" Link "NOSUBJECTS & NOUSERS"}

        - @{"TN=TONAME/S" Link "TONAME"}

        - @{"F=FOLDER/S" Link "FOLDER"}

        - @{"NH=NOHEADER/S" Link "NOHEADER"}

        - @{"GS=GROUPSIZES/S" Link "GROUPSIZES"}

   @{b}*@{ub} Special values:

        - @{"SORTBY" Link "SORTBY"}

   After calling UMSMailStat the statictics will be built, these can be
redirected into a file or i.e. to the printer via the AmigaDOS
redirection option. Just the statistics will be redirected, but not the
copyrightnote, progress-display etc., these will always be written into
the console-window. See @{"Examples" Link "Examples"}.

   If you want statistics to be in german or french language, you
should copy the supplied 'UMSMailStat.catalog' from the
Locale/Catalogs/<language> directory of the distribution archive to
your corresponding Locale:Catalogs/<language> directory (provided that
you have installed WorkBench v2.1 or higher).


@EndNode

@Node "NAME" "UMSMailStat.guide/NAME"
@Toc "Usage"

NAME
====

   The name (or alias) of a user in the UMS messagebase.

   NAME must always be specified.


@EndNode

@Node "PASSWORD" "UMSMailStat.guide/PASSWORD"
@Toc "Usage"

PASSWORD
========

   The password of the user specified by @{"NAME" Link "NAME"}.

   PASSWORD must always be specified, the empty password "" is valid!


@EndNode

@Node "SERVER" "UMSMailStat.guide/SERVER"
@Toc "Usage"

SERVER
======

   The server, on which the user wants to login (default is "default"
:-).

   If you want to login to another server, just must also specify the
keyword SERVER, i.e. SERVER=OtherServer.


@EndNode

@Node "GROUP" "UMSMailStat.guide/GROUP"
@Toc "Usage"

GROUP
=====

   The group(s) in your UMS messagebase, which should be scanned for the
statistics. Instead of a group you can also give an AmigaDOS-pattern and
all groups matching this pattern will be taken into the stats.

   GROUP must always be specified.


@EndNode

@Node "DATE & DAYS" "UMSMailStat.guide/DATE & DAYS"
@Toc "Usage"

DATE (AmigaDOS-date) and DAYS (Numeric)
=======================================

   These two arguments determine the period about which the statictics
will be built: DATE means the stats are starting with this day, DAYS is
for the length of the period in days.

   If DATE is stated sole, stats will be built just for this one day.

   If you state DATE and DAYS, stats will be built for all messages
that were written in the DAYS days after DATE (including DATE).

   If you just state DAYS, only messages of the past DAYS days,
including today will be scanned. If you neither give DAYS nor DATE, all
messages of that group will be scanned.


@EndNode

@Node "CDATE" "UMSMailStat.guide/CDATE"
@Toc "Usage"

CDATE (Switch)
==============

   When using this option together with @{"DATE" Link "DATE & DAYS"}, messages will not be
selected by their import- but their creation-date, i.e. the date the
message has really been written by the author. This option will only
take effect with an UMSServer v11.22+.

   You may use CD as an abbreviation for CDATE.


@EndNode

@Node "MAXUSERS" "UMSMailStat.guide/MAXUSERS"
@Toc "Usage"

MAXUSERS (Numeric)
==================

   Determines how many users will be in the list. If you state 10,
you'll get a top-10 and so on. 0 means all users will appear in the
list.

   This option will override the settings of the UMS-variable
@{"UMSMailStat.MaxUsers" Link "UMSMailStat.MaxUsers"}.

   You may use MU as an abbreviation for MAXUSERS.


@EndNode

@Node "MAXSUBJECTS" "UMSMailStat.guide/MAXSUBJECTS"
@Toc "Usage"

MAXSUBJECTS (Numeric)
=====================

   Same as @{"MAXUSERS" Link "MAXUSERS"}, but for the subject-list. 0 also means all subjects
will appear.

   This option will override the settings of the UMS-variable
@{"UMSMailStat.MaxSubjects" Link "UMSMailStat.MaxSubjects"}.

   You may use MS as an abbreviation for MAXSUBJECTS.


@EndNode

@Node "QUIET" "UMSMailStat.guide/QUIET"
@Toc "Usage"

QUIET (Switch)
==============

   UMSMailStat will just show the statistics, but not copyright,
progress-display etc.


@EndNode

@Node "REALBYTES" "UMSMailStat.guide/REALBYTES"
@Toc "Usage"

REALBYTES (Switch)
==================

   If this option is used, UMSMailStat determines the real length of the
messagetext instead of using the faster headerfield TextLen resulting in
more accurate byte result but also slows down scanning speed.

   You may use RB as an abbreviation for REALBYTES.


@EndNode

@Node "QUOTECHECK" "UMSMailStat.guide/QUOTECHECK"
@Toc "Usage"

QUOTECHECK (Switch)
===================

   Turns on the quote-analyzer to generate statictics about "quoting
habits", See @{"Quote statistics example" Link "Quote statistics example"}.

   UMSMailStat will try to find out how many bytes of a message have
been quoted from another message and show these values in a seperate
column of the statistics.

   The quotecheck can be configured by the @{"QUOTECHARS" Link "QUOTECHARS"} commandline-option
and the UMS-variables @{"UMSMailStat.Quote.Chars" Link "UMSMailStat.Quote.Chars"} and
@{"UMSMailStat.Quote.CheckFirstNChars" Link "UMSMailStat.Quote.CheckFirstNChars"}.

   Note: when using QUOTECHECK the @{"REALBYTES" Link "REALBYTES"} option will automagically
be used. QUOTECHECK also slows down scanning speed.

   You may use QCHK as an abbreviation for QUOTECHECK.


@EndNode

@Node "QUOTECHARS" "UMSMailStat.guide/QUOTECHARS"
@Toc "Usage"

QUOTECHARS
==========

   Configures which characters will be considered as quote-introducers
in the messagebody. If one of the characters in this string is found in
the first 10 characters (see note below) of a line, that line will be
considered as a quoted line. By default, UMSMailStat just uses ">" (as
this appears to be the standard quote-introducer).

   This option will override the settings of the UMS-variable
@{"UMSMailStat.Quote.Chars" Link "UMSMailStat.Quote.Chars"}.

   Note: by using the UMS-variable @{"UMSMailStat.Quote.CheckFirstNChars" Link "UMSMailStat.Quote.CheckFirstNChars"}
you can configure how many chars at the beginning of a line shall be
checked for being quote-chars.

   You may use QCHRS as an abbreviation for QUOTECHARS.


@EndNode

@Node "NOSUBJECTS & NOUSERS" "UMSMailStat.guide/NOSUBJECTS & NOUSERS"
@Toc "Usage"

NOSUBJECTS and NOUSERS (Switches)
=================================

   If using one of these options, the subject-statictics (NOSUBJECTS)
or the author-statistics (NOUSERS) will not be printed. It is also
possible to use both option then only the global statistics will be
shown.

   You may use NS as an abbreviation for NOSUBJECTS and NU as an
abbreviation for NOUSERS.


@EndNode

@Node "TONAME" "UMSMailStat.guide/TONAME"
@Toc "Usage"

TONAME (Switch)
===============

   Using this option a list of adressee will be generated instead of a
list of authors. I.e. for each message the receiver will be determined
instead of the author.

   You may use TN as an abbreviation for TONAME.


@EndNode

@Node "FOLDER" "UMSMailStat.guide/FOLDER"
@Toc "Usage"

FOLDER (Switch)
===============

   When using this option the @{"GROUP" Link "GROUP"} pattern will be interpreted as
folders in your personal mail, so no public messages will be scanned.

   You may use F as an abbreviation for FOLDER.


@EndNode

@Node "SORTBY" "UMSMailStat.guide/SORTBY"
@Toc "Usage"

SORTBY
======

   This option determines how the lists will be sorted. You must
specify one of the options below with the SORTBY argument, i.e.
SORTBY=QUOTEPERCENTAGE.

   Possible options are:

    @{b}MSGS (messages)@{ub}
          This is the default, so you may or may not specify this.
          Sorting will be done in this order:

             @{b}*@{ub} number of messages

             @{b}*@{ub} number of bytes

    @{b}BPM (bytes per message)@{ub}
          Sorting will be done in this order:

             @{b}*@{ub} bytes per message

             @{b}*@{ub} number of bytes respectively number of messages

    @{b}QUOTEPERCENTAGE@{ub}
          Sorting will be done in this order:

             @{b}*@{ub} quotepercentage

             @{b}*@{ub} quotebytes

    @{b}QUOTEBYTES@{ub}
          Sorting will be done in this order:

             @{b}*@{ub} quotebytes

             @{b}*@{ub} number of bytes

   If all the values to order by are exactly the same, the users and/or
subjects will get the same ranking and will be ordered alphabetically.


@EndNode

@Node "NOHEADER" "UMSMailStat.guide/NOHEADER"
@Toc "Usage"

NOHEADER (Switch)
=================

   When using this switch, the global statistics will not be printed.

   You may use NH as an abbreviation for NOHEADER.


@EndNode

@Node "GROUPSIZES" "UMSMailStat.guide/GROUPSIZES"
@Toc "Usage"

GROUPSIZES (Switch)
===================

   This option will only become active, when scanning multiple group,
i.e. if @{"GROUP" Link "GROUP"} is a pattern, and will print the overall size of all
messages in each group in the grouplist at the beginning of the
statistics. The sizes may vary depending on the usage of @{"REALBYTES" Link "REALBYTES"} or
@{"QUOTECHECK" Link "QUOTECHECK"}.

   Using GROUPSIZES slows down the scanning speed.

   You may use GS as an abbreviation for GROUPSIZES.


@EndNode

@Node "Configuration" "UMSMailStat.guide/Configuration"
@Toc "Main"

Configuring UMSMailStat
***********************

   Since version 1.14 UMSMailStat some variables in the ums.config have
been introduced:

   @{b}*@{ub} @{"UMSMailStat.MaxUsers" Link "UMSMailStat.MaxUsers"} (since v1.14)

   @{b}*@{ub} @{"UMSMailStat.MaxSubjects" Link "UMSMailStat.MaxSubjects"} (since v1.14)

   @{b}*@{ub} @{"UMSMailStat.Quote.Chars" Link "UMSMailStat.Quote.Chars"} (since v1.16)

   @{b}*@{ub} @{"UMSMailStat.Quote.CheckFirstNChars" Link "UMSMailStat.Quote.CheckFirstNChars"} (since v1.16)

   These options can be used to override some of UMSMailStat's hardcoded
limitations for statistics-generation, but will themselves be
overridden by their pendants on the commandline.


@EndNode

@Node "UMSMailStat.MaxUsers" "UMSMailStat.guide/UMSMailStat.MaxUsers"
@Toc "Configuration"

UMSMailStat.MaxUsers
====================

   CLI pendant: @{"MAXUSERS" Link "MAXUSERS"}

   I.e. if you insert the following line into your ums.config (v11
notation)

       ( UMSMailStat.MaxUsers "20" )

   UMSMailStat would now list 20 users in the users-statistics by
default.


@EndNode

@Node "UMSMailStat.MaxSubjects" "UMSMailStat.guide/UMSMailStat.MaxSubjects"
@Toc "Configuration"

UMSMailStat.MaxSubjects
=======================

   CLI pendant: @{"MAXSUBJECTS" Link "MAXSUBJECTS"}

   I.e. if you insert the following line into your ums.config (v11
notation)

       ( UMSMailStat.MaxSubjects "0" )

   UMSMailStat would now list all subjects in the subjectstatistics by
default.


@EndNode

@Node "UMSMailStat.Quote.Chars" "UMSMailStat.guide/UMSMailStat.Quote.Chars"
@Toc "Configuration"

UMSMailStat.Quote.Chars
=======================

   CLI pendant: @{"QUOTECHARS" Link "QUOTECHARS"}

   I.e. if you insert the following line into your ums.config (v11
notation):

       ( UMSMailStat.Quote.Chars ">%:" )

   UMSMailStat would now consider ">", "%" and ":" as quote-introducers
by default. This option will only be used if the @{"QUOTECHECK" Link "QUOTECHECK"} option has
been specified in the commandline.


@EndNode

@Node "UMSMailStat.Quote.CheckFirstNChars" "UMSMailStat.guide/UMSMailStat.Quote.CheckFirstNChars"
@Toc "Configuration"

UMSMailStat.Quote.CheckFirstNChars
==================================

   No CLI pendant

   When the @{"QUOTECHECK" Link "QUOTECHECK"}-option is used, UMSMailStat by default checks the
first 10 characters of each line of a message to see if it contains a
quote-char (see above). If you think this is too much/low, you can use
this to change the margin to your personal needs. I.e. the following
line in your ums.config (v11 notation)

       ( UMSMailStat.Quote.CheckFirstNChars "20" )

   would let UMSMailStat check the first 20 characters of every line.

   Note: A large margin may (I haven't tested it) result in a further
slow-down of scanning speed.


@EndNode

@Node "Examples" "UMSMailStat.guide/Examples"
@Toc "Main"

Examples
********

   Some example-calls:

@{b}UMSMailStat olf secret GROUP=de.comm.software.ums >topten.asc@{ub}
     Build statistics about the group de.comm.software.ums and write
     them into file topten.asc.

@{b}UMSMailStat olf secret GROUP=de.comm.software.ums DATE=23-Nov-93@{ub}
     Build statistics about the 23rd of november 1993 in
     de.comm.software.ums.

@{b}UMSMailStat olf secret GROUP=de.comm.software.ums DATE=23-Nov-93 DAYS=7@{ub}
     Build statistics about the week starting with the 23rd of november
     1993 and ending on 29th of november.

@{b}UMSMailStat olf secret GROUP=de.comm.software.ums DAYS=7@{ub}
     Builds statistics of the last week, including today as well.

@{b}UMSMailStat olf secret GROUP=de.comm.software.ums QUOTECHECK QUOTECHARS=">|:"@{ub}
     Build statistics about the group de.comm.softeware.ums and also
     checks the quoting habits, using ">", "|" and ":" as
     quote-introducers.

   Here are some example outputs:

   @{b}*@{ub} @{"Standard statistics example" Link "Standard statistics example"}

   @{b}*@{ub} @{"Quote statistics example" Link "Quote statistics example"}


@EndNode

@Node "Standard statistics example" "UMSMailStat.guide/Standard statistics example"
@Toc "Examples"

Standard statistics example
===========================

     --------------------------------------------------
     Mailstatistics for group comp.sys.amiga.programmer
     --------------------------------------------------
     
     Statistics from 16.04.1995 to 18.04.1995.
     
     Bytes:          166730
     
     Authors             67   Bytes/Author:          2488
     Messages:          105   Bytes/Message:         1587
     Subjects:           65   Bytes/Subject:         2565
     
     The most bytes in one message, being 5197, wrote
     Doug Walker about 'Re: Explain .library'.
     
     Top 3 Authors
     =============
     
     -------------------------------+-------------+--------------+--------------+
      Pl. Name                      |   Messages  |     Bytes    |  Bytes/Msg.  |
     -------------------------------+-------------+--------------+--------------+
       1. Doug Walker               |      6,  5% |   13483,  8% |  2247    660 |
       2. Jan Krutisch              |      4,  3% |    9430,  5% |  2357    770 |
       3. James Cooper              |      4,  3% |    6628,  3% |  1657     70 |
     -------------------------------+-------------+--------------+--------------+
       E  Sum/Average               |     14, 13% |   29541, 17% |  2110    523 |
     -------------------------------+-------------+--------------+--------------+
     
     
     Top 3 Subjects
     ==============
     
     -------------------------------+-------------+--------------+--------------+
      Pl. Subject                   |   Messages  |     Bytes    |  Bytes/Msg.  |
     -------------------------------+-------------+--------------+--------------+
       1. Zoom gadgets              |      5,  4% |    7939,  4% |  1587      0 |
       2. Interrupts                |      4,  3% |    7454,  4% |  1863    276 |
       3. A brand new OS            |      4,  3% |    6406,  3% |  1601     14 |
     -------------------------------+-------------+--------------+--------------+
       E  Sum/Average               |     13, 12% |   21799, 13% |  1676     89 |
     -------------------------------+-------------+--------------+--------------+
     
                                        UMSMailStat 1.16 (18.4.95) by Olaf Peters

   What do the fields mean?

                                           1)  2)         3)  4)      5)     6)
     
       2. Interrupts                |      4,  3% |    7454,  4% |  1863    276 |

  1. Number of messages about this subject (or this author)

  2. percentage of all messages

  3. Amount of bytes about this subject (or this author)

  4. percentage of all messages

  5. average bytes per message

  6. difference between 5. and the overall average of bytes per message

   The E-row at the end of the table states the sum/averages for the
chosen number of table-entries. It doesn't have to correspond with the
global values!


@EndNode

@Node "Quote statistics example" "UMSMailStat.guide/Quote statistics example"
@Toc "Examples"

Quote statistics example
========================

     --------------------------------------------------
     Mailstatistics for group comp.sys.amiga.programmer
     --------------------------------------------------
     
     Statistics from 16.04.1995 to 18.04.1995.
     
     Bytes:          115281 (30% quoted)
     
     Authors             67   Bytes/Author:          1720
     Messages:          105   Bytes/Message:         1097
     Subjects:           65   Bytes/Subject:         1773
     
     The most bytes in one message, being 4739, wrote
     Doug Walker about 'Re: Explain .library'.
     
     Top 3 Authors
     =============
     
     ---------------------------+-----------+-------------+-------------+-------+
      Pl. Name                  | Messages  |    Bytes    | Quotebytes  | B/Msg |
     ---------------------------+-----------+-------------+-------------+-------+
       1. Doug Walker           |    6,  5% |  10600,  9% |   3646, 34% |  1766 |
       2. Jan Krutisch          |    4,  3% |   7346,  6% |   3176, 43% |  1836 |
       3. James Cooper          |    4,  3% |   4658,  4% |   2628, 56% |  1164 |
     ---------------------------+-----------+-------------+-------------+-------+
       E  Sum/Average           |   14, 13% |  22604, 19% |   9450, 41% |  1614 |
     ---------------------------+-----------+-------------+-------------+-------+
     
     
     Top 3 Subjects
     ==============
     
     ---------------------------+-----------+-------------+-------------+-------+
      Pl. Subject               | Messages  |    Bytes    | Quotebytes  | B/Msg |
     ---------------------------+-----------+-------------+-------------+-------+
       1. Zoom gadgets          |    5,  4% |   5464,  4% |   2472, 45% |  1092 |
       2. Interrupts            |    4,  3% |   5415,  4% |   1622, 29% |  1353 |
       3. A brand new OS        |    4,  3% |   4331,  3% |    916, 21% |  1082 |
     ---------------------------+-----------+-------------+-------------+-------+
       E  Sum/Average           |   13, 12% |  15210, 13% |   5010, 32% |  1170 |
     ---------------------------+-----------+-------------+-------------+-------+
     
                                        UMSMailStat 1.16 (18.4.95) by Olaf Peters

   What do the fields mean?

                                     1)  2)        3)  4)        5)  6)       7)
     
       2. Interrupts            |    4,  3% |   5415,  4% |   1622, 29% |  1353 |

  1. Number of messages about this subject (or this author)

  2. percentage of all messages

  3. Amount of bytes about this subject (or this author)

  4. percentage of all messages

  5. number of bytes from 3. that have been considered as quotes in the
     messages.

  6. percentage of quotes relative to 3.

  7. average bytes per message

   The E-row at the end of the table states the sum/averages for the
chosen number of table-entries. It doesn't have to correspond with the
global values!


@EndNode

